==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Marjoram
<hw>Mar"jo*ram</hw> <pr>(m⟦aum⟧r"j⟦osl⟧*r⟦ait⟧m)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>
<ety>[OE. <ets>majoran</ets>, F. <ets>marjolaine</ets>, LL.
<ets>marjoraca</ets>, fr. L. <ets>amaracus</ets>, <ets>amaracum</ets>,
Gr. <grk>'ama`rakos</grk>, <grk>'ama`rakon</grk>.]</ety>
<fld>(Bot.)</fld> <def>A genus of mintlike plants (<gen>Origanum</gen>)
comprising about twenty-five species. The sweet marjoram (<spn>Origanum
Majorana</spn>) is peculiarly aromatic and fragrant, and much used in
cookery. The wild marjoram of Europe and America is <spn>Origanum
vulgare</spn>, far less fragrant than the other.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

